    "humanBeat": "A developer wants to hand a Linux user one executable that launches normally instead of asking which JVM, distribution package, or installer they have.",
    "visualIdentity": "Java bytecode moves through ParparVM and Zig, sheds unreachable code and resources into a compact native ELF, then runs on two architectures.",
    "bespokeVisualization": "The compilation chain keeps system GTK libraries visible beside the self-contained application so portability claims remain precise.",
    "heroJourney": {
      "identity": "Codename One and native Linux desktop delivery are introduced.",
      "problem": "A Java archive needs a JVM, while native Linux delivery faces package managers, architectures, libc compatibility, and desktop dependencies.",
      "difficulty": "A binary linked on a new distribution can fail on an older one, resources must travel with the executable, and graphics, media, browser, storage, and networking need native implementations.",
      "intervention": "ParparVM translates reachable bytecode to C and Zig compiles it against an old glibc target into one resource-embedded ELF.",
      "victory": "The developer ships an x64 or arm64 native application that launches without a target JVM and uses the Linux desktop stack."
    },
